ver?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Streptococcus pyogenes","Staphylococcus aureus","Streptococcus agalactiae","Streptococcus pneumoniae","Group B streptococcus"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ERheumatic fever is an autoimmune response triggered by infection with \u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus pyogenes\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as Group A Streptococcus. The immune system\u0027s response to this bacterium can lead to inflammation in various parts of the body, particularly the heart, joints, skin, and central nervous system.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options are incorrect:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E is a common cause of skin infections and abscesses but is not associated with rheumatic fever.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus agalactiae\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E (Group B Streptococcus) is primarily associated with neonatal infections and is not a trigger for rheumatic fever.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus pneumoniae\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E is a common cause of pneumonia and meningitis but does not lead to rheumatic fever.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EGroup B streptococcus\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E is another name for \u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus agalactiae\u003C/em\u003E and is not linked to rheumatic fever.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that not all infections with Group A Streptococcus lead to rheumatic fever. The condition develops in a small percentage of untreated cases, typically two to three weeks after the initial streptococcal infection.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Rheumatic fever is an autoimmune response triggered by infection with Group A 